metadata.title: Artbreeder. Draw me an Electric Sheep. | by Merzmensch | Towards Data Science
metadata.h1: Artbreeder. Draw me an Electric Sheep.

all_paragraphs: Nothing is original. And yet everything is. Already at the beginning of the XXth century, Dadaists, Surrealists, and later MERZ artist Kurt Schwitters explored this fact. They mixed found materials to new collages and 3D-assemblages. Countless fragments of countless realities became numerous new visions.

Contemporary experiments with Artificial Intelligence bear similar beautiful fruits. You may recognize intertextuality behind new works, but here they are — new worlds, for you. What initially began with Google Deep Dream became a multifaceted visualization of Androids’ dreams.
We can see now what AI is dreaming about Electric Sheeps, the world, and the rest.

Last year I wrote about GANbreeder, an application by Joel Simon (http://www.joelsimon.net/). A user-friendly BigGAN model set, pre-trained on ImageNet, Kaggle sets, and other visual databases. Popularization and democratization of Data Visualization. It allows generating visual masterpieces from existing DNAs — in a collaborative process with other users/artists/viewers, even without elaborated knowledge of Data Science (not every artist can Python).
The newest project by Joel brings you to the next dimensions of #AI generated artworks. Breathtaking:
At the moment, there are five sections: General, Portraits, Albums, Landscapes, and Anime Portraits. (The project is in ongoing development, so new models and functions are emerging all the time).
Ian Goodfellow, Research Staff Scientist by Google Brain, mentioned one year before the giant leap in face generation efforts by AI:

When 2014 AI-generated faces still looked almost like a pareidolia Mars Face, 2018 was already a breakthrough in photo-realistic fake faces generation (remind the viral page ThisPersonDoesnotExist.com with absolutely astonishing results produced with StyleGAN).
Now you can do it yourself. In Section Portraits, you will find four functions:
So let’s create a new person from an existing set of portraits. Choosing “Random” will bring you to a list of existing images within “Artbreeder”:
As you see, not only photorealistic faces are available, but also stylistically different models. StyleGAN is showing Style Transfer in its best way here. Let’s choose the male with glasses.
What you see here is the initial set of possibilities. On the top right side is the actual modification panel with
Below you can see already generated images by various users.
All image features are Neural Network Layers, which you can change pro-actively or per random.

This modification method is the one you have the least control over. Everything you can do is to change the percentage of Similarity vs. Difference. The more different image you define, the more different results you get (Fig. 2). You can fine-tune the picture when it already almost meets your expectations.

A classical Style Transfer model. You choose another image (existing within Artbreeder) as a target (or source, it depends) — by modification face and style parameters, you can transfer style between two chosen images. So you can merge pictures or change their style.

The most potent modification way: by pro-active changing the percentage of every layer, you can directly alter specific features. In Fig 4. you can see the previous portrait of the male spectacle wearers — but by changing layers Age, Eyeglasses, Gender practically extremely different image emerges. Parameter Concept_art is a hidden Style Transfer layer switching from photo-realistic image to a hand-written sketch or painting.
The second icon under the image is Lineage. It shows the “genealogical tree” of the portrait:
In our case, it’s a short family tree. You will find also iteratively modified images with a long story in Artbreeder.

This is a new feature, which makes Artbreeder more to an art lab. It isn’t pure GAN-only farm anymore. It does mean: you can upload your images. They might be proceeded and changed by Adversarial Networks in this or another way. Sometimes not really how you imagined it.

For example, uploading this famous Avant-gardist portrait of Dadaist Hans Arp (with a paper disc hiding his left eye) causes “correction” by GAN in its interplay between Generator and Discriminator — and restores his invisible eye (changing the gaze):
This is the actual intersection with the real world (with all its implications like copyright, data privacy, etc. — users should use it wisely). Then there is Term of Use, of course.
So this happens if you transfer the style of the Hans Arp portraits above to my photo:
Or Style Transfer for me with Klaus Nomi:
Upload function multiplies the possibilities enormously.

The great addition to the static image generation. Choose the keyframes (existing portraits) — and AI will generate the transitions between the images in an almost magic way. You can choose the duration and also the transition mode.
This keyframe sequence produces fascinating footage:
You can notice various Style Transfer transitions between keyframes — mesmerizingly weird.
This is the actual core behind former GANbreeder (also produced by Joel Simon) — polished and running with new models. Here you can generate a lot of things.

Remember, back to 2018, the big breakthrough with BigGAN? You could give the Tensorflow based GAN model a task to generate a specific motif — and results were already convincing (try it out with Colab Notebook).
With Artbreeder you can generate worlds from scratch.
Like in portraits, you have here following functions:
Sneaking into Random will probably confuse you at most. Other than faces you will find here all possible chimeras, phantasms, and unexplainable visuals.
The modifying functions are here similar to generating Portraits.
With the prominent exception of “Edit-Genes”.

As you can see, the layers here don’t represent face features like in Portrait — they rather represent motifs, almost Platonic eidos. These “Genes” are “Categories” from “Category-conditional sampling” in BigGAN: topics of the visual database, which were labeled and used for training.
In Fig. 10 you can observe which categories are building base for the visuals (and in which proportions): Comic book, Eskimo Dog, Palace, etc.
We even can tell about the semantic etymology of the image here.
This transformative art generation is a genuinely new way of re-mapping our reality. So let’s create a new image from scratch — in the next function.
First of all, you need to select a gene (a labeled layer, a Neural Network Synapse within BigGAN):
This is a category library which hid the list of contents. Let’s choice “Architecture” as our first gene.

As you see, this was a careful labeling work (which is not always the case). BigGAN is trained on countless images of the same category, so choosing a gene can produce pretty different image of the same topic. So let’s take “Caste” as the first gene — and the second one will be from the category “Instruments.”

Now you see what I mean with labeling. It’s always a human factor. Images from ImageNet (and pretty much other image databases as well) are labeled by people, sometimes without a clear concept about its purpose. What is labeled here as a music instrument is actually in most cases a person playing this instrument. The implication is apparent — instead of objects, it will generate humans. For Weak AI it’s all about patterns to be defined.
But now let’s combine a “castle” with an “organ”:

Both — castles and organs — are recognizable, even if one cannot distinguish between inside and outside. Pretty dreamish imagery. You know this feeling when you wake up and try to recall the recent dream — the visuals are interchanging and metamorphosing, vanishing, slipping. Confusing your brain, which is trying to find the most uncomplicated conception.

Pretty much the same as with portraits — and results are overwhelming. Again, it’s like the visualization of a dream, just in this case you can even see — or pause — the video, which won’t help your consciousness with better recognition.
Here is a sample of General Animation:
10.000 Album Covers was a database for training Neural Networks in the Section “Albums”.

This is something very special — others than Portraits or General, Albums is a mimetic mix of text, layout, and imagery. Far is the time of Artificial General Intelligence. We are still working with Weak AI — the semantics behind texts are missing. It’s rather computational attempts to recreate text.
Similar to previous models we have here following functions:
Keep in mind that “fonts” and “writings” here belong to composition. It cannot be modified separately as a layer.
It’s rather about an aesthetic perception than comprehension.
The variety of styles, motifs, and logotypes inspires for more.

This section demonstrates how perfect it can emerge the Neural Networks training on myriads of images. In this case — landscapes are mostly perfect. Or it’s probably our perception — our brain is also better trained on nature imagery than on other motives. So we don’t realize existing glitches or visual mistakes since our perception skips unnecessary elements.
You know already how the functions work:

Like in Albums — here you have to try out, to mix, to modify. There are no real “genes” of landscapes (at least at the moment), but with randomization of parameters you can generate wonderful exemplars:
As a recent addition, Joel extended the selection with the Anime portraits, the Anime Model by legendary Gwern (visit also Gwern’s project ThisWaifuDoesNotExist.com).

Joel Simon is the hero behind Artbreeder. But there is also folk in Artbreeder Discord-Server, who discusses, exchanges ideas, advises how to adapt the best UX, geeks out about newest AI achievements, argues about Terms of Service and privacy, shares newest Artbreeder generated works. Teamwork par excellence.
Development of Artbreeder is very dynamic — because Joel reacts quickly to users’ ideas and corrections.
Best User Experience I had with digital products so far.
That’s why probably the next days after this article is published, Artbreeder may get new functions or may change its interface. So, what are you waiting for? Dive in and join Artbreeder.
Indeed, which use cases are relevant for image generation by Artbreeder? How can you apply the results?
…just to name some of the interesting usages.
Do you have other ideas for applying the portrait generation?

UPDATE. I’ve found a great article with the similar title on GANs, which was published a year ago by Dr. Ernesto Diaz-Aviles, the Co-Founder and CEO at Libre AI about interesting attempts to draw sheeps with help of AI/ML. Kind of Disclaimer: probably this merge between Antoine de Saint-Exupéry and Philip K. Dick a typical for our comprehension of creativity and Artificial Intelligence. So, I haven’t copied the title, in case you wonder. It’s rather the obvious consequence of XXIst century. :-)
Futurist. AI-driven Dadaist. Living in Germany, loving Japan, AI, mysteries, books, and stuff.
